Expected Outcomes
After completing this lab, students should have:

Functional Python scripts for analyzing AndroidManifest.xml files
Working credential extraction tools for mobile applications
Understanding of common mobile security misconfigurations
Generated security assessment reports identifying vulnerabilities
Knowledge of automated security testing approaches
Key findings should include:

Debuggable applications in production
Backup enabled allowing data extraction
Exported components without proper protection
Hardcoded API keys and credentials
Sensitive permissions without justification
Troubleshooting Tips
Issue: XML parsing errors

Verify XML file is well-formed and properly encoded
Check for special characters that need escaping
Ensure file path is correct and accessible
Issue: No credentials detected

Verify regex patterns match credential formats
Check file encoding (use UTF-8)
Ensure search is recursive through all subdirectories
Issue: Script execution errors

Confirm Python 3 is installed: python3 --version
Install missing modules: pip3 install lxml
Check file permissions: chmod +x script.py
Conclusion
This lab demonstrated mobile application security assessment techniques focusing on configuration analysis and credential extraction. Students learned to identify common security misconfigurations in AndroidManifest.xml files and extract hardcoded sensitive data from configuration files.

Key takeaways:

Mobile apps frequently contain hardcoded credentials and API keys
AndroidManifest.xml misconfigurations expose apps to security risks
Automated tools significantly improve security assessment efficiency
Regular security audits are essential for mobile application security
Proper credential management and secure configuration practices are critical
These skills are fundamental for mobile application security testing and vulnerability assessment in real-world scenarios.
